[1] Congo DR (Katanga province)
Date: Mon 16 Oct 2015
Source: Radio Okapi [in French, transl. Mod.LM, edited]
http://www.radiookapi.net/2015/10/16/actualite/sante/ex-katanga-428-personnes-sont-mortes-de-rougeole-depuis-janvier-2015


Ex-Katanga: 428 dead of measles since January 2015
-----------------------------------------------------
30 000 cases of measles were reported, of which there were 428 deaths since January 2015 in the province of the former Katanga. The Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA) that delivered this information Friday, 16 Oct 2015, reported that in the space of 3 months, the number of affected health zones has more than doubled, from 11 at the end of May 2015 to 26 at the end of September 2015.

In the 1st week of October [2015], the former Katanga recorded nearly 30 000 cases of measles since January [2015], 80 percent of the cases throughout the country. 428 people died. Compared to the previous year [2014] where the province reported approximately 10 000 cases in the same period, the number of cases has almost tripled in 2015, according to the OCHA report.

Several suspected measles cases are registered in more than half of the 11 health zones of Lubumbashi, even if the outbreak is confirmed so far only in a health zone, said the same report. Of the 24 health zones for outbreaks reported in the province, 8 have already received support.

OCHA invites the authorities of the province and the health stakeholders to review the health system to effectively fight against this epidemic by offering including access to basic health care, the regularity of vaccination, access to drinking water.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-FRA
<ProMED-FRA@promedmail.org>

[Measles, a viral disease preventable by vaccination, continues to be a major public health problem. Yet there is an effective vaccine available, well tolerated and available for free, against the disease. Measles is even about to become endemic in our countries because the disease is found in all periods of the year. Previously, it was an epidemic disease occurring during the cold and dry season when a hot, dry wind (called harmattan) flows and disappearing during the rainy season, like meningitis. To overcome this disease, you need a high rate of vaccine coverage. To achieve high vaccine coverage requires a broad awareness of populations to vaccinate children, who are most affected. But the disease can even affect adults who are not vaccinated.

An interactive HealthMap/ProMED-mail map is available at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3809958,34141. - Mod.BM]

